          em Factors
          |  of Cervical Cancer(Causes).
        h2 Many sexual partners.
        p.
          The greater your number of sexual partners — and the greater your partner's number of sexual partners — the greater your chance of acquiring HPV.
          
        h2 Early sexual activity.
        p Having sex at an early age increases your risk of HPV.
        h2 Other sexually transmitted infections (STIs).
        p.
          Having other STIs — such as chlamydia, gonorrhea, syphilis and HIV/AIDS — increases your risk of HPV.
          
        h2 A weakened immune system.
        p You may be more likely to develop cervical cancer if your immune system is weakened by another health condition and you have HPV.
        h2 Smoking.
        p Smoking is associated with squamous cell cervical cancer.
        h2 Exposure to miscarriage prevention drug.
        p If your mother took a drug called diethylstilbestrol (DES) while pregnant in the 1950s, you may have an increased risk of a certain type of cervical cancer called clear cell adenocarcinoma
