            Some questions that are frequently being asked.
            
        .accordion.accordion-flush.px-xl-5#faqlist
          .accordion-item(data-aos="fade-up", data-aos-delay="200")
            h3.accordion-header
              button.accordion-button.collapsed(type="button", data-bs-toggle="collapse", data-bs-target="#faq-content-1")
                i.bi.bi-question-circle.question-icon
                | 
How long does it take for cervical cancer to develop?

            #faq-content-1.accordion-collapse.collapse(data-bs-parent="#faqlist")
              .accordion-body.
                
                Cervical cancer begins to develop when normal cells in the lower portion of the uterus change or mutate. They first become pre-cancerous. When pre-cancerous cells grow out of control, they may spread to nearby tissue, as well as other parts of the body, and if left untreated, they may grow into a mass, or tumor.
                
          
            .accordion-item(data-aos="fade-up", data-aos-delay="300")
            h3.accordion-header
              button.accordion-button.collapsed(type="button", data-bs-toggle="collapse", data-bs-target="#faq-content-2")
                i.bi.bi-question-circle.question-icon
                | 
Should I consider preventive surgeries if I have risk factors for cervical cancer?

            #faq-content-2.accordion-collapse.collapse(data-bs-parent="#faqlist")
              .accordion-body.
                
                Unlike with breast or ovarian cancer, there is no recommended prophylactic surgical procedure to prevent cervical cancer. But one important step women can take is to follow medical screening guidelines, which call for getting a Pap smear every three years for women aged 21 to 29, and getting tested for HPV beginning at age 30—and to get the HPV vaccine.
                
         
            .accordion-item(data-aos="fade-up", data-aos-delay="400")
            h3.accordion-header
              button.accordion-button.collapsed(type="button", data-bs-toggle="collapse", data-bs-target="#faq-content-3")
                i.bi.bi-question-circle.question-icon
                | 
Will I need surgery?

            #faq-content-3.accordion-collapse.collapse(data-bs-parent="#faqlist")
              .accordion-body.
                
                Surgery to remove the cancer is often part of the treatment regimen for women with cervical cancer. Surgery may be combined with chemotherapy and/or radiation or targeted therapy. Ask your doctor about the specific treatment options available to you
                
         
